---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Calibration from "../components/Calibration.astro";
import { arena, backtest, summary } from "../lib/data.js";
import { num, pct } from "../lib/format.js";

const s = summary();
const bt = backtest();
const ar = arena();
const w = s.wwiii;
const suites = Object.entries(bt);
const countrySuite = bt["country/deaths/sb≥25"];
const MODEL_NOTES = {
  "pool:views+persist": "equal-weight average — the arena's best forecast",
  "pool:all-three": "equal-weight views+tocsin+persistence",
  views: "Uppsala VIEWS, main_dich at each horizon",
  tocsin: "this engine, walk-forward-clamped, one-step",
  persistence: "country's trailing-12-month hit rate",
  climatology: "country's full-history monthly rate",
};
---

<Base title="Methods" description="How the base rates are computed, and how well they calibrate.">
  <h1>Methods</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The engine answers one kind of query: what fraction of comparable unit-years met a measure.
    It answers with an explicit ladder — the unit's own history, its region, the world — every
    level conditioned on recency, with empirical-Bayes shrinkage and class sizes shown. If a
    class is thin, you see that. Full write-up lives in the repo (docs/method.md).
  </p>

  <h2>Recency buckets</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Conflict is sticky: the strongest single predictor is whether violence happened recently.
    Every estimate conditions on the unit's bucket — <b>active</b> (met the measure last year),
    <b>recent</b> (2–3 years ago), <b>dormant</b> (4–10), <b>cold</b> (11+ or never observed).
    The unit's bucket is taken at the edge of observation, so unobserved years never decay it.
  </p>
  {countrySuite && (
    <div class="card viz">
      <h3>What the buckets are worth (walk-forward, country grain, sb ≥25)</h3>
      <table class="data">
        <thead><tr><th>bucket</th><th class="n">unit-years</th><th class="n">mean predicted</th><th class="n">observed</th><th class="n">Brier</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          {Object.entries(countrySuite.by_bucket).map(([b, v]) => (
            <tr>
              <td><span class={`badge bucket-${b}`}>{b}</span></td>
              <td class="n">{num(v.n)}</td>
              <td class="n">{v.mean_p}</td>
              <td class="n">{v.observed}</td>
              <td class="n">{v.brier}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  )}

  <h2>Is the engine calibrated? (walk-forward backtest)</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Every unit-year since the burn-in gets a pseudo-forecast computed from strictly earlier
    data, scored against what happened — {num(suites.reduce((t, [, v]) => t + v.n, 0))} of them.
    Dots on the diagonal = calibrated. Country grains hold the line end to end; the dyad grain
    runs optimistic at the top (dyad episodes terminate more than pooled persistence implies) —
    shade active-dyad continuation priors down a few points.
  </p>
  <div class="grid-2">
    {suites.map(([name, suite]) => (
      <Calibration name={name} suite={suite} />
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>The Global War Index</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    The percentile rank (0–100) of a year's global organized-violence deaths — state-based +
    non-state + one-sided best estimates — within the whole GED era (1989–present). No weights,
    no smoothing, reproducible from the committed tables. The current partial year is annualized
    from candidate months for display only and never ranked.
  </p>

  <h2>The WWIII panel, operationally</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <table class="data">
      <thead><tr><th>tile</th><th>definition</th><th class="n">years true</th><th class="n">base rate</th><th class="n">conditional now</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {[
          ["≥1 interstate war", w.hero],
          ["≥1 interstate conflict", w.any_interstate],
          ["P5 primaries active", w.p5_activity],
          ["P5 primaries at war", w.p5_war],
          ["P5 forces both sides at war (wide)", w.p5_war_wide],
        ].map(([label, b]) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{label}</td>
            <td style="font-size:12.5px;color:var(--ink-2)">{b.definition}</td>
            <td class="n">{b.years_true}/{b.years}</td>
            <td class="n">{pct(b.unconditional, 1)}</td>
            <td class="n">{b.conditional.rate == null ? "—" : pct(b.conditional.rate, 1)}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="viz-legend" style="margin-top:12px">
      {w.notes.map((n) => <span>· {n}</span>)}
    </div>
  </div>

  {ar && (
    <>
      <h2>The arena — TOCSIN vs other models</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Retrospective head-to-head on VIEWS's native target — {ar.target} — with every model
        predicting the next 12 months from the same historical vantages using only
        information available then. {num(ar.n)} scored country-months across
        {" " + ar.vantages.length} vantages; VIEWS numbers are used untransformed
        (their main_dich calibrates against the ≥25 threshold: detected, not assumed).
      </p>
      <div class="card viz">
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>model</th><th></th><th class="n">Brier</th><th class="n">skill</th>
              <th class="n">h1–3</th><th class="n">h4–6</th><th class="n">h7–12</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {Object.keys(ar.models).sort((a, b) => ar.models[a].brier - ar.models[b].brier).map((m) => (
              <tr>
                <td><b>{m}</b></td>
                <td style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted)">{MODEL_NOTES[m]}</td>
                <td class="n">{ar.models[m].brier}</td>
                <td class="n">{pct(ar.models[m].skill_vs_climatology, 1)}</td>
                <td class="n">{ar.by_horizon["h1-3"][m]}</td>
                <td class="n">{ar.by_horizon["h4-6"][m]}</td>
                <td class="n">{ar.by_horizon["h7-12"][m]}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="viz-legend" style="margin-top:12px">
          <span>· The best forecast in the arena is nobody's model — it's the equal-weight pool
            (combining diverse forecasters beats the best member; zero fitted parameters).
            VIEWS leads the singles; TOCSIN is better on {num(ar.head_to_head.tocsin_better_on)} of {num(ar.n)} months
            (the quiet mass) but pays more on transitions — and adds no diversity to a
            persistence pool, because at this grain TOCSIN <i>is</i> calibrated persistence</span>
          <span>· persistence nearly ties VIEWS: the standing result of this field, reproduced</span>
          <span>· {pct(ar.provisional_share, 0)} of outcomes are candidate-month provisional</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </>
  )}

  <h2>The journal's rules</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    Questions pin a UCDP measure, scope, threshold, and window at ask-time, and resolve
    mechanically: <b>yes</b> the moment the cumulative measure crosses the threshold
    (decided on the crossing date), <b>no</b> once available data covers the window.
    Resolutions leaning on candidate months are provisional until an annual release confirms —
    a flip is recorded and the score moves. Scoring is paired Brier, challengers vs the engine's stored prior,
    on the same questions; forecasts and priors timestamped after a question's deciding date
    never score.
  </p>

  <h2>Sources & rights</h2>
  <p class="lede">
    UCDP/PRIO Armed Conflict Dataset, UCDP Dyadic, GED {s.release} and monthly candidate events;
    Gleditsch–Ward state system. Free for research use with attribution — full citations and the
    layered rights table in DATA-RIGHTS.md. Nothing here is a prediction of intent; these are
    historical frequencies with their reference classes shown.
  </p>
</Base>
